    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I sighed as I read yet another self-justification for urban S.U.V. driving -- ''I have two kids so I need it'' (''Drivers Offer a Collective Ho-Hum as Gasoline Prices Soar,'' Business Day, March 30).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I sighed as I read yet another self-justification for urban S.U.V. driving -- ''I have two kids so I need it'' (''Drivers Offer a Collective Ho-Hum as Gasoline Prices Soar,'' Business Day, March 30).</p>
        <p>I drive a Skoda Octavia (a Volkswagen Jetta, more or less) with a 1.6-liter engine. Two car seats fit just fine in my back seat, I can fit the stroller and shopping in the trunk, and traffic allowing, I can do 90 miles an hour on the motorway. And with gas at the equivalent of $6.70 a gallon, I won't be trading up any time soon.</p>
        <p>Yes, Americans, we can manage with smaller cars. Three years in Europe has taught me that much.</p>
        <p>Alexis Rosoff Treeby  London, March 30, 2007</p>
      </block>
